"This above all: to thine own self be true And it must follow, as the night the day Thou canst not then be false to any man/Farewell, my blessing season this in thee!" - Polonius, Hamlet We all possess our own (absolute) political views. In recent years, the polarization of

these views have grown ever more extreme. Indeed, this Presidential election has delivered perhaps the most polarized views in American history. In some quarters I have been roundly criticized by those who feel my stock market views have been impacted by my personal view of

President Trump - readily seen in my Twitter account. Most of my critics, almost by definition, have been pro-Trump. I try strenuously to only write in my Diary about how the President's behavior, actions and policies might impact equities. Like anyone else, I get that analysis

wrong, at times, and right at other times. Ironically, some of the same observers who have criticized me for being concerned about the President's actions/policies impact on the markets might be doing the same thing right now - as it relates to their view of the markets.

Specifically, those are maintaining a bullish view - even, arguably, in the face of the recent technical weakness/breakdown - believe the markets are generally overreacting to the spread of Covid-19 domestically and abroad. They are critical about the strategy of containing the

virus by shutting down certain businesses. Some, like President Trump, are against or see little value in face masks, something I and many others, like Jim "El Capitan" Cramer are very much in favor of. Just read our Comments Section yesterday!

So to my critics, I ask today, are your market views being impacted by your politics? For as William Shakespeare once wrote, "to thine own self be true." @jimcramer @tomkeene @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney @riskreversal @ScottWapnerCNBC @lizclaman @terranovajoe @guyadami
